resources.name: Submarine Cable Map
resources.notes:
Line work is stylized, not actual locations; landing points are for the city, not the building.  To get the data click 'Visualize' then select 'Map', then click the 'Download KML' link available above the map.  For landing points, modify the 'Location' dropdown menu to 'coordinates'
 from 'name', then click 'Download KML' to get the landing point data.  You can also get the data from: https://www.google.com/fusiontables/DataSource?docid=1BVxUz5t3qDmHJApb6FVckR5mJDOn_xYFocOKWnA (cables) and https://www.google.com/fusiontables/DataSource?docid=1viJdQy7bRfdGlFuVAEYLrTQ7TClIwtPKCdcpCYY (landing points).

resources.name: Social Weather Mapping with Twitter
resources.notes: US Only; geo-locates recent tweets that contain the terms "sunny", "rainy", "snowy", "windy", and "foggy". The size of the circles are determined by the number of tweets.  Previous project with KML and wider geographic range is now defunct (http://www.metaportaldermedienpolemik.net/mashup/twitter/weather/index.php)

organization.description: The Humanitarian Data Project (HDP) exists to make humanitarian and crisismapping-related datasets available to groups collecting and managing crisis data. Through datahub, HDP will be launching an open website, which will act as a one-stop shop in guiding individuals as to where humanitarian datasets exist.
